  script: >
    So if you're building a React app on Vercel, there are some patterns
    that make a huge difference in production. The biggest shift is thinking
    server-first. Most of your components should be server components by
    default, which means they render on the server and send zero JavaScript
    to the browser. You only add the "use client" directive when you actually
    need interactivity, like click handlers or state. This alone can cut
    your bundle size dramatically. For data, you want to use server actions
    instead of building API routes for everything. They let you write
    functions that run on the server but call them from your components
    like regular functions. Caching is the other big one. Vercel gives you
    a multi-layer cache, from request deduplication all the way to edge
    caching, and understanding when to use each layer is what separates
    a fast app from a slow one. The skill also covers image optimization
    with next/image, font loading with next/font, and how to structure
    your route segments so the framework can do its job efficiently.
    Basically, it's the difference between writing React that happens
    to run on Vercel and writing React that takes full advantage of
    the platform.
